{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491494"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:49:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:49:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"959"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/959"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.4,0.01,0.41,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"959"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52820"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/959"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"959"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38202"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"3542"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"910"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42181"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52820"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of a painful, swollen neck. Over the same period, she has experienced sleeplessness and a sensation of anxiety. She reports a recent sore throat and dry cough but has otherwise been well. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears mildly unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min and regular, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is tenderness and warmth over both lobes of her thyroid gland. Thyroid function testing reveals a low TSH and high levels of T3 and T4.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most helpful in confirming the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neck ultrasound","Radioactive iodine uptake scan","CT scan of the neck","Thyroid autoantibody tests","Fine-needle aspiration biopsy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is highly suggestive of subacute granulomatous thyroiditis, also known as de Quervain\u0027s thyroiditis. The clinical features include painful thyroid swelling, preceding viral symptoms (sore throat and cough in this case), and signs of transient hyperthyroidism (anxiety, tachycardia). While the diagnosis is primarily clinical, certain investigations can help confirm it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadioactive iodine uptake scan\u003C/strong\u003E is the most helpful investigation in confirming the diagnosis of subacute thyroiditis. In this condition, the thyroid gland\u0027s ability to take up iodine is markedly reduced due to inflammation and damage to thyroid follicles. A radioactive iodine uptake scan would show very low uptake, typically less than 1-2% at 24 hours, which is characteristic of this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeck ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E can show hypoechoic areas in the thyroid gland in subacute thyroiditis, but these findings are non-specific and can be seen in other thyroid conditions. While useful in evaluating thyroid nodules or differentiating between solid and cystic lesions, it is less helpful in definitively diagnosing subacute thyroiditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the neck\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used in the diagnosis of thyroiditis. It may show enlargement of the thyroid gland but provides little specific information about thyroid function or the nature of the inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid autoantibody tests\u003C/strong\u003E are more useful in diagnosing autoimmune thyroid conditions like Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis or Graves\u0027 disease. In subacute thyroiditis, autoantibodies are typically negative or present only in low titers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine-needle aspiration biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely performed in suspected subacute thyroiditis due to the condition\u0027s self-limiting nature and the pain associated with the procedure. It may be considered if the diagnosis is uncertain or if malignancy is suspected, but it\u0027s not the most helpful first-line investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s worth noting that while radioactive iodine uptake scan is most helpful in confirming the diagnosis, the diagnosis of subacute thyroiditis is often made clinically. The typical course involves a hyperthyroid phase (as seen in this patient) followed by a hypothyroid phase before returning to normal thyroid function. Treatment is generally supportive with NSAIDs or corticosteroids for pain relief.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The diagnosis of subacute granulomatous (de Quervain) thyroiditis is primarily clinical, with radioactive iodine uptake scan showing characteristically low uptake.","Subacute thyroiditis typically presents with painful thyroid swelling, preceding viral symptoms, and transient hyperthyroidism followed by hypothyroidism."],"references":["Hennessey J. Subacute Thyroiditis. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Boyce A, Chrousos G, de Herder WW, Dungan K, et al., editors. Endotext. South Dartmouth (MA)2018."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38202"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"959"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38202"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-10T12:59:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-10T13:01:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"959"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52820"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"3542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3542"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"De quervain\u0027s thyroiditis","synonyms":["Subacute thyroiditis"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-09-23T04:54:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T04:54:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},